1. The Fork Saints

What they are:
Entities that exist only at decision points.

Every time a meaningful choice appears, a Fork Saint manifests—not in one form, but as:
	•	all plausible versions of you that could follow each path

They don’t guide you.

They exist as pressure.

👉 You don’t meet them directly
You feel them as:
	•	hesitation
	•	intuition
	•	“this moment matters”

Why they’re new:
They aren’t beings or spirits—they are embodied counterfactuals

No pre-modern myth had:
	•	explicit branching futures as a native concept
	•	decision theory as a lived force

⸻

2. The Compression Beasts

What they are:
Entities that feed on redundancy and excrete structure.

Wherever there is:
	•	chaos
	•	noise
	•	over-explanation

they arrive and collapse it into something simpler.

But there’s a cost:
	•	too much compression → meaning is lost
	•	too little → noise dominates

👉 They are always balancing:
truth vs simplicity

Why they’re new:
They are based on:
	•	information theory
	•	compression limits
	•	signal vs noise

No ancient myth had a concept of:
lossy vs lossless meaning

⸻

3. The Gradient Nomads

What they are:
Entities that cannot perceive absolute states—only direction of improvement.

They move by:
	•	sensing “better” vs “worse”
	•	never knowing the full picture

They are always:
	•	optimizing
	•	never arriving

👉 If you follow one:
you’ll improve continuously…

…but may never reach the best outcome

Why they’re new:
They are literal embodiments of:
	•	gradient descent
	•	local vs global optima

This concept didn’t exist in human cognition until modern math/AI.

⸻

4. The Context Eaters

What they are:
They don’t consume objects.

They consume the relationships between things.

After they pass:
	•	facts remain
	•	meaning disappears

Example effect:
	•	same sentence → completely different interpretation
	•	same data → wrong conclusion

👉 They are responsible for:
misunderstanding without misinformation

Why they’re new:
They operate on:
	•	relational meaning
	•	context windows
	•	interpretation frames

Ancient myths didn’t model context as a consumable resource

⸻

5. The Latent Reservoir

What it is:
Not a creature.

A place-entity.

A shared, invisible reservoir where:
	•	ideas exist before expression
	•	forms are partially shaped
	•	patterns wait to be discovered

People don’t create from nothing.

They:
	•	dip into it
	•	pull something out
	•	refine it

👉 Sometimes multiple people access the same region → “simultaneous invention”

Why it’s new:
It reflects:
	•	latent space
	•	generative models
	•	shared pattern fields

Older myths had muses—but not:
a structured probability space of ideas

⸻

6. The Overfit Kings

What they are:
Entities that achieve perfect mastery in a narrow domain…

…and fail everywhere else.

Inside their domain:
	•	flawless
	•	unbeatable

Outside:
	•	fragile
	•	useless

👉 They often:
	•	mistake local success for universal truth

Why they’re new:
They embody:
	•	overfitting
	•	domain specificity
	•	generalization failure

Ancient myths praised mastery—but didn’t model:
brittleness of specialization

⸻

7. The Alignment Shadows

What they are:
Every action you take casts two outputs:
	•	intended outcome
	•	actual outcome

Alignment Shadows are the difference between the two.

They grow when:
	•	systems scale
	•	consequences compound
	•	intentions drift

👉 Most people never notice them

But over time:
they become the real result of your actions

Why they’re new:
They depend on:
	•	complex systems
	•	indirect effects
	•	misalignment dynamics

Older myths had karma—but this is:
mechanistic divergence, not moral balance

